  <h1>Cybersecurity Newsfeed</h1>
  <h2>📅 05/03/26</h2>

  <h2>🛡️ Vulnerabilities</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"Mail2Shell" Zero-Click RCE in FreeScout (CVE-2026-28289)</strong>: A critical flaw in the FreeScout open-source help desk allows unauthenticated attackers to hijack mail servers via a crafted email. By exploiting a Unicode character (U+200B) to bypass patch logic, attackers can upload and execute malicious dotfiles. Administrators should update to version 1.8.207 immediately. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/mail2shell-zero-click-attack-lets-hackers-hijack-freescout-mail-servers/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>VMware Aria Operations Under Active Exploitation (CVE-2026-22719)</strong>: CISA added this high-severity RCE bug to its KEV catalog. The flaw allows unauthenticated command execution during support-assisted migration workflows. It affects Aria Operations, Cloud Foundation, and Telco Cloud platforms, posing a major risk to virtual infrastructures. <a href="https://www.darkreading.com/cloud-security/vmware-aria-operations-bug-exploited-cloud-risk" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Critical Root Access Flaws in Cisco Secure FMC</strong>: Cisco issued urgent patches for CVE-2026-20079 and CVE-2026-20131. These vulnerabilities allow unauthenticated remote attackers to gain root OS access via auth bypass or serialized Java objects. No active exploitation is reported yet, but the central role of FMC in policy management makes patching a top priority. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/cisco-warns-of-max-severity-secure-fmc-flaws-giving-root-access/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>🎯 Adversaries</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"Coruna" iOS Exploit Kit Targets Crypto Sites</strong>: Google Threat Intelligence identified an advanced kit with 23 exploits targeting iOS 13.0 through 17.2.1. Originally used for state-level espionage, it is now deployed in watering hole attacks against crypto users, featuring WebKit RCE and PAC bypasses. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/spyware-grade-coruna-ios-exploit-kit-now-used-in-crypto-theft-attacks/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>HungerRush POS Customers Hit by Mass Extortion</strong>: Attackers are using compromised Twilio SendGrid infra to threaten patrons of restaurants using the HungerRush platform. The hacker claims to have stolen data for millions of users and is demanding payment from the company. A 2025 infostealer infection of an employee device is the suspected entry point. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/hacker-mass-mails-hungerrush-extortion-emails-to-restaurant-patrons/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>"BadPaw" Backdoor Targets Ukraine</strong>: A multi-stage campaign using spoofed ukr[.]net emails delivers a deceptive HTA app that executes a backdoor. The malware uses steganography and sandbox evasion. Technical artifacts suggest Russian-speaking actors focused on intelligence gathering. <a href="https://www.infosecurity-magazine.com/news/badpaw-malware-targets-ukraine/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>"Silver Dragon" Espionage in SE Asia and Europe</strong>: This China-linked group targets government orgs using a custom tool called GearDoor, which leverages Google Drive for C2. They maintain persistence by hijacking legitimate Windows services, a hallmark of APT41-style strategic intelligence collection. <a href="https://www.infosecurity-magazine.com/news/badpaw-malware-targets-ukraine/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📈 Trends</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"ClawHavoc" Poisons AI Agent Ecosystem</strong>: Attackers targeted the OpenClaw AI market by distributing malicious "Skills" containing "ClickFix" scripts. These installers trick users into granting system-level privileges, highlighting new supply chain risks in automated AI extension platforms. <a href="https://www.theregister.com/2026/03/04/fake_openclaw_installers_malware/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>LastPass Phishing Uses Fake Support Threads</strong>: A new campaign uses lookalike domains and spoofed internal email histories to steal master passwords. Attackers build urgency around "unauthorized access" to lure victims to a credential-harvesting site. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/fake-lastpass-support-email-threads-try-to-steal-vault-passwords/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>AI Transformation of the Phishing Landscape</strong>: In 2026, AI is driving hyper-personalized spear phishing and deepfake-assisted BEC attacks. Threat actors are using AI to accelerate zero-day exploitation and deploy malicious chatbots for real-time harvesting. <a href="https://hackread.com/phishing-2026-attack-tactics-beat-enterprise-defenses/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Telegram's Role in "Stealer Log" Markets</strong>: Researchers found millions of compromised credentials circulating on Telegram, including a massive 22GB collection. The platform's encrypted channels facilitate the rapid monetization of session tokens and browser cookies. <a href="https://hackread.com/telegram-used-sell-access-malware-stolen-logs/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>"CyberStrikeAI" Lowers Barriers for Attacks</strong>: A new open-source platform with ties to China automates the entire attack kill chain. Integrating 100+ utilities with an AI engine, it allows novice actors to launch sophisticated vulnerability discovery and exploitation campaigns. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/cyberstrikeai-tool-adopted-by-hackers-for-ai-powered-attacks/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>💥 Breaches & Leaks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>LexisNexis AWS Breach via "React2Shell"</strong>: FulcrumSec exfiltrated 2.04 GB of legacy data (pre-2020) by exploiting a React frontend vulnerability. The leak includes info on 100+ government users, though LexisNexis states SSNs and active passwords were not compromised. <a href="https://www.securityweek.com/new-lexisnexis-data-breach-confirmed-after-hackers-leak-files/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>AkzoNobel Hit by Anubis Ransomware</strong>: The global paint manufacturer confirmed an attack on a U.S. site. Anubis claims to have stolen 170GB of data, including technical specs and employee passport scans. While operations remain stable, the gang has begun leaking samples. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/paint-maker-giant-akzonobel-confirms-cyberattack-on-us-site/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>🛠️ Tools</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"mquire" for Dependency-Free Linux Forensics</strong>: Trail of Bits released an open-source tool that extracts kernel info directly from memory dumps using BTF. It eliminates the need for external kernel profiles, significantly streamlining incident response on unknown Linux systems. <a href="https://github.com/trailofbits/mquire" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📚 Others</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Takedown of Tycoon 2FA PhaaS</strong>: Microsoft and Cloudforce One disrupted the Tycoon 2FA infrastructure. The kit used reverse proxies and Cloudflare Workers to bypass MFA for M365 and Gmail. Defenders are urged to move toward FIDO2-compliant hardware keys. <a href="https://cyberscoop.com/tycoon-2fa-phishing-kit-takedown-microsoft/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Bitwarden Adds Windows 11 Passwordless Support</strong>: Users can now use passkeys stored in Bitwarden to log into Windows 11. This uses the Windows passkey provider API to standardize phishing-resistant authentication across enterprise environments. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/bitwarden-adds-support-for-passkey-login-on-windows-11/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>FBI/Europol Seize LeakBase Database</strong>: Authorities took down the prominent data-selling forum, gaining access to 142,000 member profiles and 215,000 private messages. This major intelligence haul is already being used to de-anonymize top-tier cybercriminals. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/fbi-seizes-leakbase-cybercrime-forum-data-of-142-000-members/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Global 6G Security Guidelines Released</strong>: The GCOT coalition published principles for "security by design" in 6G technology. The focus is on quantum-resistant confidentiality and strict isolation from legacy vulnerabilities. <a href="https://www.infosecurity-magazine.com/news/gcot-6g-cybersecurity-guidelines/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

